<font color="#FF0000">MAYA LIN AND RACISM</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 28  0:58:31 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I have not seen the PBS Special on Maya Lin mentioned above.  But I have not doubt that there was, and is, racism concerning just about every aspect of life in America, then and now.  <br><br>
I remember a few incidents in Danang, Vietnam, one of which I wrote home about.  It may seem petty, but an Air Force bus refused to stop for a black airman who wasn't in exactly the right spot when it had done so for white airmen at several stops prior to that one.  But these things build up, over time.  I do also remember being amoungst a group of black airman who were angry about something, and being very uncomfortable about it.<br><br>
But I feel that the closer one was to combat, the less the racism (at least, toward blacks from whites).  There was still racism pertaining to the Vietnamese though, and at times our treatment of the Vietnamese was not good.  There was a lack of respect for local customs, for their religion, and for them as a people too.  Also, since it was hard to differientiate between friend and foe, this attitude went toward all Vietnamese.<br><br>
The Vietnamese distrusted us too, and no one can wonder why.  I remember being on temporary duty from DaNang to Bien Hoa, and playing volleyball with the Vietnamese Air For squadron next door.  At first, when we set up the net, they would take our ball and not give it back.  So we stole it back, then they stole it again, and we got it back by simply saying that they could use it anytime, just come and ask for it.  And, boy they were good volleyball players too.  It took me three two-week trips down to Bien Hoa to gain their trust enough to even talk causually.  When I asked about their feelings about the war, they were as confused about it as we were.<br><br>
But should it be so amazing that there was racism then?  We still have it.  Just look at the cover of Newsweek just before the Nov. election (Oct. 28, 1996) and the unflattering characature of Mr. James Riady along with the headlines &quot;CANDIDATES FOR SALE...Clinton's Asia Connection&quot; shows that racism sells.  And, what's more disturbing is that we are still buying.<br><br>
When will we, as a society, decide to place &quot;race&quot; as a concept in the trash?  Last year, I believe, Newsweek also ran a series of articles which explained the scientific reservations concerning the entire concept of race.  We hear constantly, especially on the &quot;talk radio,&quot; discussions of blacks thinking this, whites thinking this, when in reality there is no such thing.  These are individual people, whom we are deciding should be classified a certain way.  Some societies classify people differently.  Some don't classify, and I hope that at some point we can begin to see through this &quot;race issue&quot; for what it is, simply a means of saying that we are better than somebody else.  <br><br>
Cultural differences matter; these form our being, help decide who we thing we are, and how we relate to this world.  But cultures differ even where we think race is similar; an Eskimo acquaintance of mine who was firefighting in Alaska had been on a trip to Eastern Europe, and told me this story beside a campfire in the Brooks Range, where we were fighting a natural fire (yes, we did have time to sit and talk on the fire).  He was flying home, from Siberia, when a Japanese woman came up to him and spoke to him in Japanese.  He said, &quot;Lady, I'm an American Eskimo.  I can't understand a word you're saying.&quot;  It was also interesting that the other smokejumpers on this fire would not talk to the Eskimo fire crew, nor associate with them, even when they were being eaten alive by mosiquitos (the fire surely helped keep them away).  Kinda' dumb, right?  <br><br>
Well, that pretty much sums up many American's concept of race.  Kinda dumb.  The tragedy is that this dumb concept is causing so much anguish in our society.  As my boy now says, &quot;That's guberistic.&quot;
